<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="135" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,1350,1917]" pageId="18" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1785,1809]" pageId="18" pageNumber="135">Remarks.</emphasis>
The male pygofer resembles that of 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh" authorityName="Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh" box="[779,1332,1785,1809]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Kapsa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="135" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="simlensis">
<emphasis box="[779,923,1785,1809]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="135">K. simlensis</emphasis>
Dworakowska, Nagaich &amp; Singh
</taxonomicName>
, but the connective is narrower and longer, the aedeagal shaft is thinner and the ventral process is broadened in side view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="135" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="18.[151,1436,1350,1917]" pageId="18" pageNumber="135">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1857,1881]" pageId="18" pageNumber="135">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin prefix “mega-” Latin word “processus”, referring to the large ventral process of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
